Hello

I was wondering if you would be interested in helping me; I’m helping to find homes for high school exchange students who are coming to the US in the fall (yes – despite the pandemic). We are running out of time, as schools are soon starting and these kids need to book their flights. I’m not sure if this is something you’d ever consider, but I’m including the applications for 4 students that I am seeking homes for. Maybe one of them will resonate with you. OR, maybe you’ll think of someone else that would be a good fit. At this point, because we’re running short on time, I’m looking for even Welcome Host Families. A Welcome Host Family only makes only a 6-8 week commitment. It allows a student the chance to get here while we continue to find a permanent family. You could be a hero for one of these kids! Thanks in advance for looking at the applications. I hope to hear from you!

If you have any interest or know someone I would greatly appreciate your help

Thank you so much
Dan Strouss
Local Coordinator
Concord, MI
Cell: (517) 262‑7010

Important Reminder for Concord’s graduating class of 2021. July 31st (this Friday) is the deadline for you to keep on track for earning an entry for the $500 scholarship offered by College Board. This is a task that must be completed in order to be in the running for a chance at the $40,000 scholarship. This is a wonderful opportunity to earn a scholarship. Please review the details below. We would love to see our Concord students earning any of these!

How to Qualify
Sign in to your College Board account and build a college list on BigFuture™ with at least six colleges to earn one entry in the monthly drawing.

Get Started
Search for colleges on BigFuture™ and save them to your list.…

Our Planning Team is working hard to build a plan for school in the fall. We must follow the requirements in the MI Safe Start Roadmap. Safety is a priority, but so is a high quality, developmentally appropriate education. We will improve safety protocols and hygiene routines, however, that will be done in a fashion that is developmentally appropriate. Our plan will be complete on July 27th. As such, look for announcements and information in late July and early August.

In order for us to develop accurate plans, we would appreciate it if you fill out the three question Return to School Plan survey. This data will help us develop schedules.

https://forms.gle/ZPJdD7Ev3aizpXv77

GREETINGS PARENTS OF SENIORS!
Monday, May 4th, from 11:00 a.m. to 3:00 p.m. you will be able to:
1. Pick up your student's Jostens order, which includes cap and gown
2. Class of 2020 banners and yard signs
3. RETURN your student's Chromebook, Chromebook bag and charger
4. RETURN any textbooks, library books, or books from a teacher's classroom library that your student may have borrowed
5. RECEIVE any contents from your student's lockers that they may have left

Please understand that PARENTS/GRANDPARENTS/GUARDIANS are scheduled for the pick-up/return. We will come to your car curbside at the HIgh School entrance on Monroe St. See you then!

post_text:
Congratulations to all of the students that participated in the Name that 250-year-old Tree contest. The DNR team and staff at the Mann House were very impressed with all of the entries. The top three finishers were announced this morning. The winner will have their name and the name of the tree published on a plaque that will sit beside Concord's 250-year-old oak tree in the Mann House yard.
3rd place was Zerra Reid (6th grade) she named the tree the Ethereal Tree
2nd place was Zack Stevens (3rd grade) he named the tree the Learnedness Oak
1st place was Delaney Caples (4th grade) she named the tree the Hope Oak.

Great work Zerra, Zack, and Delaney!! We are so proud of all of you!

post_text:
IMPORTANT: Families with children who received free or reduced-cost lunches at school qualify for new program. The Pandemic Electronic Benefit Transfer Program (P-EBT) provides temporary funding to address emergency food needs for families affected by the pandemic.

P-EBT food assistance benefits will go to Michigan families with students ages 5-18 that are eligible for free or reduced-price school meals. This includes families currently receiving Food Assistance Program benefits, as well as those not currently enrolled in the program. No application is necessary for eligible families to receive P-EBT benefits.

Be sure to complete an Free/Reduced Meal application if your household income has decreased for any reason? It is possible you may qualify for the new Pandemic EBT Program. Apply online @ www.LunchApp.com. For additional information: https://5il.co/fbk8

Good Morning!!

This morning we shared our gritty YellowJackets of the Week. We are honored to have these Jackets by our side in the hive. Keep on grinding it out!!! The video link will take you to the recording of the live stream.
https://youtu.be/MEWdDN_Gg3M

Look for the YellowJacket trait of next week along with Ms. Jessica's information sheet and a new work from home challenge sheet before the end of the weekend. We want to give you credit for all of your hard work, so we are developing a virtual reward system for those that have completed their challenges. Look for more information soon and keep working hard!!

We will be handing our food from 11-12:30 in the K-8 drive and drop loop.

Paper packet pick up is also today from 11-12:30 in the K-8 parking lot.

See you later today!!!

Attention Parents!

Please submit a Free/Reduced Meal Application if your family income has changed in the last 30 days. This determination CARRIES OVER for the first 30 operating days for the 2020-2021 School year. Also, you may be eligible for additional assistance as a result.

We encourage the use of our online portal at www.lunchapp.com. If that is not an option you may fill out a paper application and return during meal pickup on Tuesday/Friday.

If you have any questions please email alan.breneman@concordschools.net.

Community Open House - Today - 1 p.m - 7 p.m.

Our remodel is almost complete. The last remaining piece will be updating furniture next summer. We would like to open the schools to anyone who is interested in seeing what's happening. Anyone wishing to take a tour, please check into the office upon arrival.

We would like to apologize for this late notice. The Fall 2019 edition of The Sting was scheduled to be mailed out last week and we were made aware this morning that community members were just starting to receive them today.

post_text:
On Saturday the cross country teams traveled to Hudson where they joined 15 other schools for Regional Competition. In the girls race Skylar Thompson led the way from start to finish. Her first place finish earned her All Regional honors and a spot in the State Finals. Also congratulations to Haylee Rinehart who ran her fastest time of the season and to Natalie Sharp who ran her fastest time ever.

In the boys race Jonathan Mikovits paced the field of runners with a first place finish. He was followed by Cole Thompson in 8th, Matt Record in 12th, Bryan Smith in 15th. All four of them earned All Regional Honors. Congratulations to Cole and Adair Artis as they both ran their fastest time ever. When the team scores were added up the Boys earned the twenty second Regional Championship in school history.

This Saturday the teams will travel to MIS for the state finals. Skylar will run at 9:30am.

post_text:
Announcing the 2019 Concord Veteran's Day Essay Contest
Qualifications: Must be a current Concord High School student
Due: Monday, November 4.
Length: 250-350 words
Theme: "Freedom isn't Free"
Judging: CHS Teachers will select one winner based on representation of theme, focus on veterans, strength of message, and grammar.
Winner: will receive $100 from student counsel, will read their winning essay at our Veterans Day Ceremony at Concord Elementary on Monday, November 11 during first hour, and will be honored on social media. The winner will be announced on Thursday, November 7th. A runner-up may also be given the opportunity to read their essay at the assembly.
Submission: Email your essay as a PDF to kevin.specht@concordschools.net. Do not include your name on the document.
Questions: Contact Mr. Specht at kevin.specht@concordschools.net

post_text: CHS students attended “Just Build It” Construction/Trade Career Fair at Eastern Michigan University. Students had opportunities to speak to professionals in a variety of trades including iron workers, electricians, plumbers, sheet metal workers, brick layers, and construction. Representatives were on hand from numerous unions, MDOT, and energy companies. University of Michigan, Northern Michigan University, and Eastern Michigan University also had representatives at the event. Students then had a chance to walk the EMU campus, visit admissions and the student center as well as see some of their facilities.
